In container: in box / in bottle / in fishbowl / in trash can / in suitcase / in bag / in locker ...

—Ñ–∞–π–ª –Ω–∞ civitai—Å—Ç—Ä–∞–Ω–∏—Ü–∞ –Ω–∞ civitai

The goal of this LoHa (simply called lora below) is to improve the "in container" concept in general

As expected, concept lora is much more difficult to made and is more fragile to model switch

This LoHa is trained on ACertainy with clip skip 1 (but you can use both clip skip 1 and 2; see the the last two example images), and chances are it may not work correctly if you use a model that is far away

In face of this issue, here are some tips for the use of this lora

  1. One common strategy is to lower the weight of lora. While this might reduce some weird artifacts, the success rate of getting the concept right also decreases.

  2. You can first generate some images on ACertainty with txt2img, and then you use img2img on another model. This is what I did with the refrigerator image. You probably still need to lower lora weight in the second stage.

  3. What I do personally is to use some merge that is close to ACertainty. This is done through add difference merge with other model: AC+w(model1-model2)

Do you really need this lora?

In fact, many of these concepts can already be generated directly with the popular models. This is for example the case for in cup, in bowl, and in box.

Moreover, there are several existing loras on civitai for similar things, and they may suit better your need depending on what you want to achieve (just search in box or in container).

However, for some other concepts, such as in suitcase or in bag, it may be much easier with this lora, unless you are very good at prompting and know how to achieve it directly on your model. Apparently, the effect of the lora on each model is different, so the only way to see whether it makes a difference is to try is yourself.

Usage Guide

--

A. Lora Weight

  • 0.1 ~ 0.4 -- is to combine multiple faces or features, or if you experience overbaking

  • 0.5 ~ 0.7 -- is a balanced weight to get still accurate feature but with more flexiblity

  • 0.8 ~ 1.0 -- is to create accurate representation of the features.

B. CFG Scale

  • Lower CFG Scale means AI gets more creative and less overbaking problems.

  • Higher CFG Scale means results get very accurate with training sets and more prone to overbaking problems.

  • Dynamic CFG Threshold, using this method allows you to bump up quality and achieve photorealistic easily, but with lycoris i found out recently that this method actually lower success rate, so only use when you are composing with a Lora / model that works fine with this method.

C. Sampling Steps, High Res Fix & Upscaling

  • I like to use sampling steps at 50, with high res step at 20, or 1/2 of sampling steps.

  • I find that 2M Karras works better and faster than SDE Karras. with ERSGAN 4x+ method + ERSGAN 4x for Upscaling. This method actually gives quite good result without being too sharp or too plasticky

  • Upscaling - GPFGAN @0.25, Codeformer @0.3 & Codeformer Weight @0.15 seems to yield superior results to me.

--

Combining with Attribute LoRa / LyCoris

You may need to do your own testing, but using character weight 0.2 below attribute lora weight yields superior results, if for some reason one features persists not showing or overbake, you may want to lower the weight of the overbaked feature Lora, and then use emphasis () to boost the specific attribute you want.

DDetailer Script

If subject face is small / far away use: DDetailer Script with bbox anime face with default settings except denoiser at 0.2-0.3. You can combine this LoRa with a lot of other Style / Attire / Pose / Acts LoRa, Also works well with character LyCoris.

How to install this script? I kinda forget how because its a bit complicated beacuse you need to install stuff from venv. but a quick google search will land you somewhere in tutorial page.

Please leave a review if you have any critiques or if you find this LoRa good.

—Ñ–∞–π–ª –Ω–∞ civitai—Å—Ç—Ä–∞–Ω–∏—Ü–∞ –Ω–∞ civitai

This is a model for making eyes a bit better.

You can use it alongside existing models to generate txt2img / img2img or use it with inpainting to fix existing images.

While using alongside other LORA/LyCORIS it's best to not overdo the weight and keep it around 0.2 - 0.6

With inpainting you can use higher weights, remember that you can control the strength by playing with the denoising.

Angel Dust (Helluva Boss)

—Ñ–∞–π–ª –Ω–∞ civitai—Å—Ç—Ä–∞–Ω–∏—Ü–∞ –Ω–∞ civitai

My first LoHA/LoRA.

You need the stable diffusion LyCORIS extension in order to make this work. Otherwise you'll get an error about the LoRA layer being named wrong or something along those lines.

Base model is NAI, trained on 228 solo images of angel dust. Works fairly well on the higher end of values (0.6-1.0). 10 epochs, 3 repetitions. 2280 steps in total.

I recommend using this LoHA on a model that's good at generating furry features, such as fluffy-rock, crosskemono, or a merge between the two.

Used a combination of the LyCORIS Experiments and "How to make a LoRA" guide on Civit to figure out how to make it.

I hope you'll enjoy it!

Art - Manga style

—Ñ–∞–π–ª –Ω–∞ civitai—Å—Ç—Ä–∞–Ω–∏—Ü–∞ –Ω–∞ civitai

Manga is different from Anime. Manga style looks like Anime, but it is mainly Lineart. Anime has no line-hatching for shading, manga does.

Manga is different from comic. Manga reads from right to left. Comic reads from left to right. Also manga book often focuses in a story at a certain timeline, not like comic book with many somewhat related stories binding together in various ways.

This model is strong. Suggesting weight 0.4 to 0.7 depending on based model. Higher weight might have panels and speech bubbles.

in V3, the demo manga pages generated -manual speech bubbles n title text- with variation of the prompt

2boys, Harry potter, black_hair_glasses, Draco Malfoy, blond hair, male body focus, sorcerer man dress, (pointed hat), <lyco:mangaV3:.7>manga style lineart monochrome, bw

anypastel, dpm++2m, steps 30, no upscale.

Usage Guide

Lora Weight = 0.1-0.4 (is best for combining, be mindful that your model may contain bias towards specific face such as korean or asian), 0.5-0.7 (is good to retain original face, while not too constraining your prompt), 0.8-1 ( is to generate accurate features of the original person ).

Use Dynamic CFG Threshold

  • Mimic = 10 | Clamp percentile = 99.5

  • Min. Mimic Scale = 0, Cosine Up

  • CFG Scale Sch. = 15, Half Cosine Down

NOTE : I realized that with LyCoris Person, dynamic CFG actually lower success rate. without dynamic CFG result are more highly successful at the cost of a little less detail.

If subject face is small / far away use: DDetailer Script with bbox anime face with default settings except denoiser at 0.2-0.3. You can combine this LoRa with a lot of other Style / Attire / Pose / Acts LoRa, Also works well with character LyCoris.

Please leave a review if you have any critiques or if you find this LoRa good.
